<br>
&quot;The Tears of Veeshan&quot;<br>
<br>
Long ago occurred the tale I tell,<br>
Yet Dragons' power in Norrath still is strong.<br>
Inspire me, Tunare's blessed Muse<br>
That mortal lips might tell the tale anew,<br>
And more might hear the call against the Foe.<br>
<br>
Veeshan gave birth. Her First, a female child,<br>
Received the mighty favor of Veeshan.<br>
This Child became the cruel and wicked Queen<br>
Of Dragonkind, a fearsome Matron, who<br>
Made Norrath's lands the playground for her brood.<br>
<br>
In elder Age a Champion was born,<br>
One of whom the Prophets had foretold.<br>
Behold! He saw the terror on the land<br>
All caused by Veeshan and her evil Brood.<br>
His heart was moved to cleanse the world and so<br>
He sought enchanted armor and a blade<br>
To arm himself to vanquish Veeshan's spawn.<br>
Thus girded, to her lair he went to seek<br>
The Queen, the firstborn Child of Veeshan.<br>
<br>
The battle joined and metal clashed with Fang.<br>
Blade and claw drew blood, but both were strong,<br>
Both believed the other's end had come.<br>
Battle raged on for a day and night,<br>
Wyrm's and Warrior's blood flowed intermix'd,<br>
And still they fought upon the Dragon's Mount.<br>
<br>
The Warrior thought perhaps his end was near,<br>
That he, too, was to fall to Dragon's power.<br>
His muscles burned, and sweat poured o'er his brow.<br>
Who could keep up such a fearsome fight?<br>
And yet he knew the Dragon must not win,<br>
And that his fate must be to slay the foe,<br>
Wyrm tyrany o'erthrown by stronger Power!<br>
<br>
And with this thought impressed upon his mind,<br>
He thrust his sword once more and struck his mark!<br>
Through her eye, into her brain he pierced,<br>
And thus the Queen of Dragons lived no more.<br>
<br>
But then the world was filled with such a shriek!<br>
The mountain shook, and lightning filled the air,<br>
Veeshan felt the passing of her child,<br>
And looked to see who dared to harm the Queen.<br>
When Veeshan saw her dead upon the ground,<br>
Tears fell from Veeshan's eyes and made a Mark<br>
Upon the One who dared to slay her child,<br>
To warn her other Children to beware.<br>
<br>
And thus the ones who stand against Veeshan<br>
Are to this day marked with a Tear-shaped sign<br>
Of causes that are noble and are just,<br>
And fight the evil blight of Tyrany.<br>
<br>
 <p>Tigonie Silvanstar<br>
Warrior of the 36th Season<br>
An Elder of <a href=http://www.webhazard.net>The Tears of Veeshan<a><br>
(a.k.a. Talcee, shaman)</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uaseop.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aseop</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/23/02 3:26:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ftearsofveeshan25764frm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=38.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The story of the mark</span><hr size=1> Within the bar, the crowd roars.  Gnomes and koa'dal, Humand and Erudites stand shoulder to shoulder listening and drinking within the rough wood confines of this outpost far from Antonica.<br>
<br>
'To the TEARS!' cry some, 'Death to the Dragons!' cry others, while some faintly caress such items as they have taken from those dragons slaughtered.<br>
<br>
Aseop stands grinning near the back of the crowd, his pockets fluch with the coin, a dwarf and a barbarian passed out out at the table behind him covered with empty bottles and tankards.<br>
<br>
Aseop raises a glass, 'To the Tears and my friends among them!  May we never find our differences so great as to lead us to conflict!'<br>
<br>
With that Aseop downs the tankard and begins to move towards the exit, tossing some platninum to the young bard performing here in Fironie Vie.<br>
<br>
Aseop laughs and places a hand over his shoulder, 'Now if only I knew what my Mark meant..'<br>
<br>
